<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">a=
lgebra</a>, the <b>partial fraction decomposition</b> or <b>partial fractio=
n expansion</b> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_frac=
tion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rational fraction">rational fraction</=
a> (that is, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction_(mathemati=
cs)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fraction (mathematics)">fraction</a> su=
ch that the numerator and the denominator are both <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomials</a>) is an op=
eration that consists of expressing the fraction as a sum of a polynomial (=
possibly zero) and one or several fractions with a simpler denominator.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Partial_fraction_decomposition#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The importance of the partial fraction decomposition lies in the fac=
t that it provides <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" titl=
e=3D"Algorithm">algorithms</a> for various computations with <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_function" title=3D"Rational function">r=
ational functions</a>, including the explicit computation of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiderivative" title=3D"Antiderivative">antider=
ivatives</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_fraction_decomposition#cite_note-2"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series" title=3D"Taylor s=
eries"> Taylor series expansions</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Z-transform" title=3D"Z-transform">inverse Z-transforms</a>, and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_transform" title=3D"Laplace tran=
sform">inverse Laplace transforms</a>. The concept was discovered independe=
ntly in 1702 by both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johann_Bernou=
lli" title=3D"Johann Bernoulli">Johann Bernoulli</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Leibniz" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Go=
ttfried Leibniz">Gottfried Leibniz</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_fraction_decomposit=
ion#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In symbols, the <i>partial fraction decomposition</i> of a rational =
fraction of the form <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inlin=
e"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"dis=
play: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"=
{\textstyle {\frac {f(x)}{g(x)}},}">
  <semantics>
