\frac {f(x)}{g(x)}}=3Dp(x)+\sum _{j}{\frac {f_{j}(x)}{g_{j}(x)}}}"></span>
</p><p>where
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i>(<i>x</i>)</span> is a polynomial, and, for=
 each <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">j</span>,
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denominator" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Denominator">denominator</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i>=
<sub><i>j</i></sub> (<i>x</i>)</span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Exponentiation" title=3D"Exponentiation">power</a> of an <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducible_polynomial" title=3D"Irreduci=
ble polynomial">irreducible polynomial</a> (i.e. not factorizable into poly=
nomials of positive degrees), and
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerator" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Numerator">numerator</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i><sub><=
i>j</i></sub> (<i>x</i>)</span> is a polynomial of a smaller degree than th=
e degree of this irreducible polynomial.
</p><p>When explicit computation is involved, a coarser decomposition is of=
ten preferred, which consists of replacing "irreducible polynomial" by "<a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square-free_polynomial" title=3D"Squa=
re-free polynomial">square-free polynomial</a>" in the description of the o=
utcome. This allows replacing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poly=
nomial_factorization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial factorizati=
on">polynomial factorization</a> by the much easier-to-compute <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square-free_factorization" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Square-free factorization">square-free factorization</a>. This =
is sufficient for most applications, and avoids introducing <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_number" title=3D"Irrational number">ir=
rational coefficients</a> when the coefficients of the input polynomials ar=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integ=
ers</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=
=3D"Rational number">rational numbers</a>.
</p>
