ective" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Surjective">surjective</a>. As the t=
wo <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Vector s=
pace">vector spaces</a> have the same dimension, the map is also <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Injective" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"In=
jective">injective</a>, which means uniqueness of the decomposition. By the=
 way, this proof induces an algorithm for computing the decomposition throu=
gh <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Linear=
 algebra">linear algebra</a>.
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>K</i></span> is the field of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">=
complex numbers</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundament=
al_theorem_of_algebra" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of algebra">fundamental=
 theorem of algebra</a> implies that all  <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i><=
sub><i>i</i></sub></span> have degree one, and all numerators <span class=
=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathm=
l-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http=
