<p>This reduces the computation of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Antiderivative" title=3D"Antiderivative">antiderivative</a> of a ratio=
nal function to the integration of the last sum, which is called the <i>log=
arithmic part</i>, because its antiderivative is a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Linear_combination" title=3D"Linear combination">linear co=
mbination</a> of logarithms.=20
</p><p>There are various methods to compute decomposition in the Theorem. O=
ne simple way is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_He=
rmite" title=3D"Charles Hermite">Hermite</a>'s method. First, <i>b</i> is i=
mmediately computed by Euclidean division of <i>f</i> by <i>g</i>, reducing=
 to the case where deg(<i>f</i>) &lt; deg(<i>g</i>). Next, one knows deg(<i=
>c</i><sub><i>ij</i></sub>) &lt; deg(<i>p</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>), so one m=
ay write each <i>c<sub>ij</sub></i> as a polynomial with unknown coefficien=
ts. Reducing the sum of fractions in the Theorem to a common denominator, a=
nd equating the coefficients of each power of <i>x</i> in the two numerator=
s, one gets a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equ=
ations" title=3D"System of linear equations">system of linear equations</a>=
 which can be solved to obtain the desired (unique) values for the unknown =
coefficients.
</p>
