B_{ir}x+C_{ir}}{(x^{2}+b_{i}x+c_{i})^{r}}}}"></span>
</p><p>Here, <i>P</i>(<i>x</i>) is a (possibly zero) polynomial, and the <i=
>A</i><sub><i>ir</i></sub>, <i>B</i><sub><i>ir</i></sub>, and <i>C</i><sub>=
<i>ir</i></sub> are real constants.  There are a number of ways the constan=
ts can be found.
</p><p>The most straightforward method is to multiply through by the common=
 denominator <i>q</i>(<i>x</i>).  We then obtain an equation of polynomials=
 whose left-hand side is simply <i>p</i>(<i>x</i>) and whose right-hand sid=
e has coefficients which are linear expressions of the constants <i>A</i><s=
ub><i>ir</i></sub>, <i>B</i><sub><i>ir</i></sub>, and <i>C</i><sub><i>ir</i=
></sub>.  Since two polynomials are equal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/If_and_only_if" title=3D"If and only if">if and only if</a> their c=
orresponding coefficients are equal, we can equate the coefficients of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Like_terms" title=3D"Like terms">like =
terms</a>.  In this way, a system of linear equations is obtained which <i>=
always</i> has a unique solution.  This solution can be found using any of =
the standard methods of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_alg=
ebra" title=3D"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a>. It can also be found wit=
h <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title=3D"Li=
mit (mathematics)">limits</a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Partial_fraction_decomposition#Example_5_(limit_method)">Example 5</a>).
</p>
